                    <para>The air-actuated front-axle declutch, high and low shifter and full-torque power take-off
                        (PTO) lockup are controlled from the cab. An air plunger or electric switch, usually mounted on
                        the instrument panel, engages or disengages a mechanical clutch.
                    </para>
                    <para>An optional speed sensor measures transfer case output driveline rpm. Optional switches
                        indicate when the front axle declutch is fully engaged or disengaged.
                    </para>
                    <para>These transfer cases provide for two-speed output (high range and low range) and a neutral
                        position that is used for PTO-equipped transfer cases only. Non-PTO cases have this neutral
                        position plugged (Figure 9).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f1303509" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../figg13/g1303510.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                                 scalefitheight="272px"/>
                        <caption>Figure 9. High Range, Low Range, and Neutral Ports</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. LOW RANGE PORT</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. NEUTRAL PORT (MTC-4208 AND -4210 ONLY)</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. HIGH RANGE PORT</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <para>The front axle declutch permits shifting from all-wheel drive (AWD) to rear-wheel drive (RWD)
                        (Figure 10).
                    </para>
                    <para>The full-torque PTO option provides an outlet to drive auxiliary power devices (Figure 11).
                    </para>
                    <para>Optional switches for full-torque PTOs indicate full engagement or disengagement.</para>
